@William James I solved every puzzle this week under my average time. This one took me 19 minutes, which is fast for me, although of course there are people who can do it much faster. 

The puzzles did *feel* hard. They required more guesswork, filling in stray letters I suspected were correct from context etc. Right up until the final letter of this puzzle, I wasn't sure if I was completely on the wrong path. 

But I suspect perhaps the absence of people complaining about the puzzles being too easy was due to a gentle admonishment in the column earlier this week that crosswords are games and games are supposed to be fun. I think the implicit message was, if it's not fun, stop doing it. I've spent over an hour on a crossword, but only because I anticipated, and received, a sense of accomplishment from sticking it out. If you're not getting that, what's the point?

@Mike @Mike Here's voicing my support for Katie and CindyM. My personal cheat rule, for instance, is never to search a clue. 

Verifying my answers while flyspecking falls into a different category in my personal rule book. Before the days of online solving, I might verify my spelling by looking in the OED, or in my copy of Shakespeare or the Bible. Or consult the encyclopedia. So my own rule book grew out of that experience. 

My mother had a different set of rules. She would try her best and then turn to the answers in the back of the book, filling in each one as she learned it. She said it kept her brain active.

